Mac OS X does not have ldconfig. You have the following options:

1. Set DYLD_LIBRARY_PATH environment variable to include directory 
where your shared library resides. This approach will load/access 
your library, but will block X11 from working correctly.

2. Set DYLD_FALLBACK_LIBRARY_PATH to include your library location 
directory (like above). Since (according to "man dyld") this env 
variable should point at the system dirs as well, 
I'd recommend to add /lib:/usr/lib:/usr/local/lib to 
whatever else you'll be setting it to.

3. When linking your executable (assuming it's your code that you 
want to access the shared lib) use linker flag -rpath 
(e.g., "gcc -o tat tat.c -Wl,-rpath /opt/local/lib








